Fitzgerald uses this technique with other colors too. He gives meanings to red and pink and uses them to describe important things. He wants readers to feel a certain way about these colors and things.

San Diego County is a good place for farming. The climate is warm and sunny. Farmers grow many things here. They grow tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, and peppers. Many people want to buy food from local farms. There is a big market for organic food in San Diego. This means people want food grown without chemicals. They want organic eggs and milk too. Some farms give tours and let people visit their land. They can walk, watch birds, and have fun.

This kind of farm is good for the land and for people. The government gives money to farmers who take care of the land. They can also have people visit their farm and learn about farming. But organic farming is harder than other kinds of farming. It needs more work to get rid of bugs and weeds. Farmers need to use natural ways to make the soil good. This can be expensive. It is also harder to make money than with big farms. Small farms need more help to be profitable.

A farm in San Diego County is a good place to talk about this. The farm is near a town called Potrero. It is 160 acres of land with chaparral, grass, and oak trees. The land is near a forest. Many animals live here. Some are endangered, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the mountain yellow-legged frog. Others are getting less common and might be in danger soon, like the burrowing owl.

People have lived in this area for a long time. First, Native Americans lived here. Then, in the late 1800s, cattle ranchers and people who sold wood came. The land was used for grazing and making wood.

I looked at a real estate website and found a farm in the area. I looked at government programs to see how a small farmer can save money and help the animals. I used a real farm as an example of what someone might do.

Culture plays a big role in any kind of negotiation. Culture is not the same thing everywhere and is not a single thing. We cannot say all people from one country are the same. Understanding a culture is harder than making a general statement about it. It is more useful for a negotiator to know how a culture affects a negotiation and how its values can help or hurt the talks.

When we meet a new culture, we compare it to our own culture. We make judgments based on what we know. But it is better to accept a culture as it is and work within its rules. This is especially true when you are in a weaker position in a negotiation. If you are in a different place and country, showing respect for their traditions and values can help you have a successful negotiation.

Culture is not just about countries. Companies also have their own culture. This can be seen in how they dress, how they talk, and who they hire. Some companies work long hours, while others have a more relaxed schedule. Some people work together and help each other, while others work alone.

Understanding values is important because it helps us know why people do things. If a culture values saving face, a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or boss. If a culture values making a good deal, a negotiator will not give up easily. Knowing these things can help you have a successful negotiation.

Before you start negotiating, it is a good idea to learn a little about the other person. This can help you make a good deal. Knowing about the other person's values and culture can help you be a good negotiator.

People say, "There is no God." This is from the Bible in Psalm 14. A man named St. Anselm used this idea. Another man, Thomas Aquinas, also believed in God. Both men wrote about why God exists. We want to know who is right.

We will start by saying we think they are both right. This way, we can compare their ideas about God. If we allow them to believe in a different kind of God, it's hard to compare their arguments.

St. Anselm said people can find God in their own minds. He said we cannot think about God not being real. This means God exists because we can think about him. We don't need to look outside ourselves for proof. This idea is called faith. It means believing something is true, even if we can't show it to others.

Thomas Aquinas said people can use reason and evidence to know God exists. He didn't need faith. He used five arguments to prove God's existence: change, cause, chance, order, and harmony. He said we can know God exists by thinking about these things.

For example, if you're given a puzzle with all the pieces except one, you can still know what the missing piece looks like. You don't need to see it to know it exists.

A long time ago, in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince named Siddhartha was born. He would one day be called the Buddha, which means the leader who has found truth. Before he was the Buddha, he renounced the world and became very wise. His teachings created the religion of Buddhism.

Buddhism is now about two and a half thousand years old. It looks different from when the Buddha was alive. In the country of Sri Lanka, people celebrate an annual ceremony called the water-cutting ceremony. This ceremony is important for the people who follow Theravada Buddhism, a main part of Buddhism.

The Theravada Buddhist community has changed its ideas about the religion over time. This is because of forces inside the community and from outside. Some forces are good for Buddhism, and some are bad.

Some words are used many times in this discussion. These words are internal, external, hostile, and benign. Internal means something comes from inside the Buddhist group. External means something comes from outside the group. Hostile means something is bad for Buddhism. Benign means something is not bad for Buddhism.

Let's learn about the basic ideas of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists believe in the three jewels of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is the Buddha's teachings. The Buddha's teachings are in three groups of text. The Sutta Pitaka has all the important talks of the Buddha. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for how to live. The Abhidhamma Pitaka has ideas about the world and the universe.

Buddhists believe in some important ideas. These ideas are that there is no permanent soul, that life has suffering, and that everything changes. These ideas help people escape the cycle of death and rebirth. This cycle is called Sansara. When people become enlightened, they will no longer have desire, hatred, and delusion.

The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for how to live. Laymen have five rules: do not kill, do not lie, do not take what is not given, do not have sex with someone who is not your partner, and do not take drugs. Monks have many more rules.

The most important idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths. The first truth is that life is suffering. The second truth is that attachment causes suffering. The third truth is that suffering can be overcome.

A long time ago, the United States and Mexico were enemies for 57 years. This started in 1836 and ended in 1893. The biggest problem between them happened during the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848. The United States won and took over some land from Mexico. This included Texas and the southwest part of the United States.

Many small fights happened between the two countries. But they stopped just before World War I. The reason for the long fight was that Americans and Mexicans had different ideas about religion, culture and tradition. They also had different interests.

This is not unusual. Countries that share a border often have problems. They have different interests and ideas, which can cause disagreements. The United States and Mexico are like many other countries that have long-standing problems with their neighbors.

David M. Pletcher said, "The United States has long-standing problems with Mexico and Cuba" (p. 41). Both of these countries are close to the United States and have been enemies. Other countries in Latin America have good relations with the United States.

A problem between the United States and Mexico was about religion. Many years ago, Americans were against Catholicism and monarchies. This was also true during the Cold War, when the United States and the Soviet Union were enemies. But this time, the problem was about the two countries' different religious ideas.

The United States and Mexico did not trust each other because of the way the English and Spanish treated them in the past. This made it hard for them to have good relations.

Diehl and Goerts listed 17 problems between the United States and Mexico during the 57-year fight. Most of these problems were about land and border issues. There were many fights between bandits and outlaws from one side of the border to the other. But when the United States and Mexico used force to control their borders, the problem started to go away.

Schmitt said the problem started to go away when Mexico needed the United States for help (p. 109). The United States also changed its goals from getting more land to helping Mexico economically (p. 110).

Fifteen years ago, I became sick with a disease I did not know I had.

I was a nurse. I chose this job because I wanted a safe and secure life. I did not have those things when I was a child. My friends told me, "You will always have a job. People will always get sick."

I wanted to be a scientist or a journalist. But I chose nursing. I am now 46 years old and single. I have no money. I am unable to work. To this day, I am sick. I get money from the government because I am unable to work. But after 15 years, I have nothing.

I struggle every day to stay safe and happy. But I know one thing is true. I would not have made it without the help of my family and friends. They were strong and helped me when I was weak.

My point is this: bad things will happen in life. There are no guarantees. We must work together to help each other.

I agree we should not rely too much on the government. But I think we should trust and help each other. This is how our country was built. Our ancestors helped each other and shared what they had.

They did not cross the country alone. They helped each other and worked together.

So, be prepared. I am prepared. I have a special bag with food, water, and a first aid kit. I have flashlights and candles in case of a power outage. But most importantly, get to know your neighbors. They can help you when you need it.

The question is: Why do living things change over time? Are there limits that control how they change? In 1917, a scientist named D'Arcy Thompson said, "Even now, zoologists do not know how to describe simple forms in math." This is still true today. Recently, scientists used math to study how mollusks grow their skeletons.

Our study is trying to figure out how to use math and experiments to learn about how living things change over time. We are studying a group of animals called Prunum. We used special pictures of their skeletons to create math formulas. These formulas can help us understand how their skeletons changed over time.

A shell is like a tube that moves through space as the animal grows. The shell has many turns, called whorls. Each whorl is like a spiral that grows around a center line. The speed at which the whorls grow can be different. A line between each whorl is called a suture. The biggest whorl is the last one, called the body whorl. The other whorls are called the spire. The tip of the spire is the apex, and the other end is the base.

We can look at shells from different angles. When we see the opening of the shell, it is called an apertural view. When we see the top of the shell, it is called an apical view.

To count the whorls, we look at the shell from the top and draw a line where the first suture starts. We can then count the whorls from that line. We can also use math to draw a path of the shell's growth.

This path can be represented mathematically and graphically. Once we have a math formula, we can change the parameters and see how the mollusk's skeleton grows.

Indonesia's rate of baby and child deaths has not changed much in the last ten years.  The country is making progress in some areas, but not enough to meet its goals for child and mother health by 2015.  There are many reasons for this problem.  These reasons will be discussed below.  They show that Indonesia needs to make its health system stronger, not just improve programs for specific health problems.

Indonesia is doing better in getting skilled health workers to deliver babies.  Now, 72% of births have a skilled worker present.  But this number includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot help if there are problems during delivery.  So, improvements in this area are not as good as they seem.  In addition, fewer children under five with diarrhea are being treated by health professionals. Data on taking care of new mothers is also incomplete, but it shows that this is a big problem.

Too few babies are delivered by C-section.  This is 4% of all births.  This number shows another problem.  In cities, 7% of babies are delivered by C-section.  But in the countryside, it is only 2%.  This means that healthcare is not available equally across the country.  People in cities are getting better healthcare than people in the countryside.

Another problem is that wealthy people are getting better healthcare than poor people.  There is a 27% gap in how often people use healthcare services, depending on how much money they have.  Poor people are not using healthcare services because they cannot afford it.

So, the question is how to improve healthcare for babies and mothers.  Should Indonesia make a plan to solve a specific problem, or should it make the healthcare system stronger?  Some people think that solving a specific problem is a good idea.  This approach has specific goals and can show fast results.  But there are some problems with this approach.  If Indonesia spends a lot of money on one health problem, it may not have enough money for other health problems.  Also, there may be too many programs doing the same thing, and they may not be working together.

Two kinds of books are called Victorian novels. They are classics from a long time ago. These books are about the rich people of the time. But two books, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They have many strange and mysterious parts. These parts make the characters in the books more interesting. They help readers understand what the characters think and feel.

In one book, Oliver Twist, a boy named Oliver has many strange dreams. These dreams show what is inside Oliver's heart. They show his pain and what he knows about the world around him. In another part of the book, Oliver remembers a shooting. He relives the shooting in his mind, like he is dreaming. This shows how scared and helpless Oliver is. He had no control over what happened to him. He was forced to suffer pain and fear. This makes the reader think that Oliver feels like giving up. He has no power over what happens to him.

Another book, Wuthering Heights, is also a mystery. It has a strange and scary atmosphere. Time is not clear in this book. It is like day and night are mixed up. The days are very long, but they are also very short. The nights are very quiet, but they are also very brief.

These two books show that sometimes bad things happen to people. They have no control over these things. These books help readers understand how people feel when they are suffering.

I worked with young students in an after-school program. They were in elementary school. I helped them with many subjects, but I was best with English and reading. One boy, Adrian, had trouble reading. He was in third or fourth grade. He could say some words correctly, but others not. It was strange. He was Latino, but he spoke perfect English. I worked with him, but we had problems. Then I met his mother. She did not speak English. She only spoke Spanish. I knew a little Spanish, but it was not very good. We talked a little bit. Then I understood the problem. Adrian could read, but he did not know the English alphabet very well. I am not sure if this helped him, but I hope he is better now.

I tell this story because many students have trouble with languages in school, especially in California. It is not always easy for students who speak English well to read. I think everyone knows this is a problem. What can we do? In Adrian's case, he needed help with the alphabet and pronunciation. But for students who do not speak English very well, the solution is more complicated. There is no one answer. We need a combination of things. These are the dual language system, mainstream classes, private tutors, ESL classes. None of these things will fix the problem by itself.

The dual language system is a good idea. It is not just for students who speak Spanish. All students can benefit. Studies show that students in bilingual education programs do better in school. Many people are afraid of this idea. They think it is a waste of money and that most students will not benefit. But this is not true. If we use this system in all schools, all students will benefit. But how can we do this? Do we need all teachers to speak two languages? No, this is not possible. But we can have special helpers who speak two languages.

We are told from a young age that there is something bigger than us in the world. Some people go to church or temple to learn about it. Others look inside themselves for answers. Many follow the same religion as their parents, but some people do not believe.

We search for our own path in life. We try to understand what is important to us. This is called our spirituality. We look for a way to guide us through life.

One day, my father and I sat on our front porch. It was raining. The sound of the rain on the roof was loud. My father looked out at the rain. He seemed sad. He was not eating much and was losing his hair. He looked thin.

I wanted to talk to him about how I would miss him when he was gone. But I was afraid. Talking about it would make it more real. So I hugged him and sat close to him. We looked out at the rain together.

My father died in December when I was twenty-two years old. He was sick for a long time. The doctors said he would not get better. But he lived a little longer because of medicine. I did not want to watch him die. I wanted to remember him when he was alive.

I did not say any prayers when my father died. I did not think God was listening to me. I felt alone and sad. I curled up in my bed for three days. No one called me to ask how I was doing.

The Gothic novel is a mix of old and new ideas. It is called an oxymoron, which means two things that do not go together. Ian Watt says this in his book The Rise of the Gothic Novel. 

In the past, people did not like the Gothic novel. They said it had no real depth. But some people praised it for its spooky and exciting parts. The first Gothic novel was The Castle of Otranto. It was written by Horace Walpole. He used old and new ideas to create a new way of writing.

Walpole used old theatrical ideas and new ideas from modern novels. He called it "A Gothic Story." The Gothic novel uses many old ideas from medieval times. These ideas come from theater, buildings, and customs. People thought the word "gothic" was old-fashioned when The Castle of Otranto was published. They thought it was not as good as modern ideas.

The combination of old and new ideas makes the Gothic novel special. It is why the Gothic novel was popular for a long time and remains interesting even today. 

One important idea in Gothic novels is chivalry. Chivalry is a code of honor for knights. It was used in medieval times. The idea of chivalry is used in The Castle of Otranto. It is important because it represents what a good knight should be: brave, honest, and skilled. 

Gothic writers used the idea of chivalry to say that the world had lost its good values. They wanted to remind people of the good old days. The writer of The Castle of Otranto, Horace Walpole, wrote during a time of political trouble. He was unhappy with the way society was. He thought that people had lost their good qualities. This idea is seen in his character, Frederic. He is a prince, a leader, and he has been through hard times. He is described as a gallant and courteous knight. This is an exaggeration, but it shows how the idea of chivalry was important in the Gothic novel.

Supply chain management is the way goods move from the customer's order to the final product. This process includes moving goods from raw materials to the customer. The term supply chain management was created in 1982 by a consultant named Keith Oliver. He described the steps to follow to plan, implement, and control the supply chain to make customers happy quickly and efficiently.

There are six key parts of a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these parts to give the best service to customers.

Production is the first step in the supply chain process. It is the base of the supply chain. Production decides how and when goods will be made. Managers must know what customers want. They look at the market to understand customer needs. The market shows what customers want.

Once managers know what customers want, they decide what goods to make and how many to make. They also decide where to make these goods. They choose a place that is good for making things in large amounts and with high quality, keeping customer needs in mind.

After deciding where to make goods, managers focus on planning workloads and taking care of equipment. Production is a very important part of the supply chain. Every detail is important. If details are not planned well, it can cost the company time and money.

For example, I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target. They have a plan for every part of their business. They have a design for employee uniforms and a plan for receiving shipments from trucks. Having plans helps companies work smoothly and without confusion.

The second key part of supply chain management is supply. Supply is about making good decisions about a company's strengths and partnerships. A company may have many parts that make different things. Managers decide which part is best for each job. They may also decide to work with other companies to make things. This is called outsourcing. Companies outsource to save time and money.

The manager's goal is to make things quickly and at a low cost. This is called velocity.

Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign says.

Ellen Page, a famous actress, stands alone on a street corner. She holds a piece of cardboard above her head with a sad message. The sign says: "Hitler is alive in Burma." Burma is a country in Southeast Asia. The government there is very bad. Many people do not like the government.

In 2007, people in Burma started protesting. They were very unhappy with their government. The protests were led by many Buddhist monks. They wore yellow robes. The people of Burma started to support the monks. At first, the government allowed the monks to gather but then the government became angry. The government used force against the monks. The military invaded monasteries and hurt many people. Foreign journalists were arrested. A Japanese reporter named Kenji Nagai was killed in 2007. He was reporting on the protests. Many people were killed. But few people know the real number. Colonel Hla Win said more than 13 people were killed. He said the number is in thousands.

This is not new. Governments want to control people and stop them from speaking out. This has been happening for a long time. In ancient Rome, the leaders said they were chosen by gods to rule. In Japan, the emperor is considered a god. Our president, George W. Bush, met with a man named Ted Haggard. He is a leader of a group that wants to help the government.

There are many examples of bad things that have happened. In 1989, many people in China were unhappy with their government. They gathered in Tiananmen Square to protest. Many people were killed. The government said 200-300 people were killed. But some groups said it was 2,000-3,000 people. In Rwanda, many people were killed in the 1990s. The government helped to kill people because of their ethnic group. Hitler's government in Germany was very bad. They killed many Jewish people.

Duke Ellington's music is famous because of his long life and his ability to make great music. He kept composing and directing his orchestra for a long time. Ellington was a good pianist, but he was a better composer. He wrote many complex pieces that showed the special talents of each musician in his orchestra. These pieces were often very good for soloists, who could improvise freely. Ellington also wrote pieces with strong melodies that suited each musician's style. He was very good at creating a good sound for his orchestra as a whole, making each piece unique.

In many pieces, Ellington used the voice as a musical instrument. He did this to add color and texture to his music. One early example is Creole Love Call, a slow blues piece. This piece has six parts. Each part is different, but they all work well together. In the first part, the singer and the reeds play a call-and-response pattern, with the singer singing smoothly and then more loudly. In the second part, a trumpet plays a solo. In the third part, a clarinet plays a fast, high melody, and the piano plays a syncopated pattern. The fourth part is like the first part, but with more instruments. In the fifth part, the reeds play the call-and-response pattern, and the brass and rhythm sections play together in a special way. In the sixth part, the singer and the reeds play the call-and-response pattern again, but this time the singer sounds like a saxophone. The last part is a short tag with a vocal run and a strange ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of the voice in his music is just one example of his style. His music often has a lot of different sounds and textures, which makes it very interesting. He was a good composer because he knew how to use the special talents of each musician in his orchestra. He also knew how to create good sounds for his orchestra as a whole.

In his next pieces, such as Hot and Bothered, Ellington used his skill at writing tight compositions and his ear for sound color. In this piece, a call-and-response pattern between a trumpet and a singer creates a rich and complementary sound. In another piece, It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing), Ellington used a trombone to introduce the melody. These are just a few examples of Ellington's great ability to make music.

She had a feeling that something was missing. This feeling started when she was fourteen and getting older. It was still there three years later, at seventeen. She wanted something, but she didn't know what. She wanted a person, not a thing. But she didn't like any boys. Some boys tried to show her attention, but she didn't feel anything.

She thought about this a lot. She tried to figure out what was wrong. She thought of different ideas, but none made sense. So she continued living her life, thinking about her feelings.

Her home was usually a peaceful place. Her parents were good people. They never argued with each other. They rarely argued with her. They wanted her to be independent and have her own ideas. Her personality was strong, and her parents were calm. This made her a happy person.

But today was not a peaceful day. She walked around the house looking for ideas. She heard a loud cry from the kitchen. She quickly went to the room and saw her mother on the floor in pain. Her mother was saying "Ow" in short breaths. The daughter ran to her mother and put a hand on her to help. "I need you to take me to the hospital," her mother said. The daughter helped her mother to the car.

At the hospital, she smelled strong cleaning smells and sickness. She was too worried about her mother to be scared. She carried her mother quickly and called for help. Doctors came and took her mother to be seen. The daughter sat and worried.

Her mother fell off a step stool while trying to get something from a high cabinet.

This study was to see if following the "Mediterranean Diet" helps prevent heart disease and stroke. The study looked at how a "Mediterranean Diet Score" relates to these problems. The Mediterranean Diet is a healthy eating plan that includes many plant foods, like fruits, nuts, and whole grains, and less saturated fat and animal products.

Past studies showed that eating this way can help people live longer and have a lower risk of heart disease. But these studies did not look at stroke or stroke deaths. This new study wanted to find out more about the relationship between the Mediterranean Diet and stroke.

The study followed 74,886 women who were 38 to 63 years old. These women were part of a big study of 121,700 nurses in 11 states in the US. The researchers counted how well each woman followed the Mediterranean Diet six times between 1984 and 2004. They used a food diary to ask the women about what they ate.

The study found that women who followed the Mediterranean Diet closely had a lower risk of heart disease and stroke. They also had a lower risk of death from heart disease or stroke. The women who ate this way were about 29% less likely to have a heart attack or stroke.

The researchers also looked at other factors that could affect the results, like age, smoking, weight, and physical activity. They found that the women who followed the Mediterranean Diet closely were less likely to have heart disease or stroke even after taking these factors into account.

Overall, this study shows that following the Mediterranean Diet can help prevent heart disease and stroke in women.

In the year two thousand seven, a big financial problem happened in the United States of America. Many people lost their jobs, the value of homes went down, and some very big companies went out of business. This problem is still happening today. We need to ask why this problem happened and how to stop it. 

The financial problem was caused by bad choices made by leaders. They made banks and companies give loans to people who could not pay them back. These loans were given to people who did not have enough money. When these people could not pay their loans, the banks did not have enough money to pay back the people who had given them the money. This made a big problem for the banks and the whole economy.

A long time before this happened, in the year nineteen ninety-nine, the President of the United States wanted to stay in office for a second time. To do this, he made rules that made it easier for people to get loans. This made it more likely that people would not be able to pay back their loans. A man named Steven Holmes from the New York Times wrote about this in nineteen ninety-nine. He said the company that makes many of the loans for homes, called Fannie Mae, was under pressure to make more loans to people who do not have a lot of money. This could cause problems in the future.

The problem with the loans was that some of them were not good. Some people got loans that they could not afford to pay back. This made the banks and the whole economy very sick. The banks had too much money tied up in these bad loans. When the people who took the loans could not pay them back, the banks lost a lot of money. This made a big problem for the economy.

The government and the banks made a system that was too complicated. They used many different kinds of loans and sold them to other people. This made it difficult for people to understand what was happening with their money. The banks and other companies got a lot of money from these loans, but they did not have enough money to pay back the people who had given them the money.

The problem was so big that many banks had a lot of debt. The top five banks in the United States had a total of four trillion dollars of debt. This is a very big number. The government had to step in to help the banks and the economy. The government took control of two big companies called Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac. They had a lot of debt, five trillion dollars, and the government had to take care of it.

Exposition is a problem for many writers. It is the part of a story where the writer tells too much about the past or a situation. This can be boring for the reader. They might fall asleep or stop reading. A writer's goal is to 'show' the reader what is happening, not 'tell' them.

For example, if a character meets someone and tells them too much about their past, this can be boring. It is better to show the reader how the character feels and what they think through their actions and words.

Think about a story where a woman meets her husband. She tells the reader that they met, got married, and he was murdered in front of her. The reader might expect this to take two pages, but it would be better for the writer to show how the husband loves his wife and how she feels about him. This way, the reader can become emotionally involved and care about the story.

A writer needs to add 'meat' to the story, not just bones. This means showing the reader the characters and their feelings, not just telling them about the plot.

Sometimes, it is tempting to rush past certain details. For instance, a character might tell the reader about their past, such as being in the Air Force or owning a gas station. But this can be boring. It is better to show the reader through the character's actions and words.

A good writer knows how to balance telling and showing. They make the story interesting and engaging for the reader.

I watched two news programs from Columbus, Ohio. The first one was on NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The main story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who hurt his wife. His name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his picture, and he looked very bad. The news program did not spend much time on this story. It said he hurt his wife many times and was arrested.

I think they spent the right amount of time on this story. 

The next story was about a man named Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and was very badly hurt. There was no one arrested yet. The police were investigating. This story seemed short. I think it was because the victim was a black man. In the past, I have noticed that when a black person is a victim of a crime, they do not get as much attention. 

The news program talked about a hole in a helicopter. They said it was shot with a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. They are offering a five-thousand-dollar reward for information about the shooter.

They also said there will be rain and thunderstorms on Saturday. The temperature will be warm.

They talked about a robbery at a store on Clime Road. A man robbed the store. The news program said he was a black man and was wearing a hoodie. They said he was tall and heavy. I thought they spent too much time talking about his skin color.

Another story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug dealer from Texas. He was convicted of selling marijuana in Ohio. The news program said he was sentenced to 25 years in prison. They also said he was Hispanic. I do not think that was important to the story.

There is a strong connection between brothers. It is a connection that is very hard to break. Inside this connection, many feelings exist. They include love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers understand each other better than anyone else. They see themselves in their brother. When things are very bad, the true nature of this connection is clear. It can be good or bad. When these feelings are clear, they can cause a lot of problems. To understand the feelings that come from being brothers, you must deal with the problems that come with them.

When one brother looks at another and sees himself, he sees himself the way he really is. He sees his true character in his actions and the consequences of those actions. The story “The Scarlet Ibis” shows this connection between brothers. The story is about two brothers and the strong feelings that come with their bond. These two brothers go on a journey through a beautiful place. They have a lot of strong feelings, like pride and hurt. In the end, only one brother lives.

The story shows what the brothers feel through the main character, Doodle, and how he acts with his brother. It also shows the feelings of the narrator, who tells the story. The narrator's feelings influence how the main character sees the world. This affects how he acts.

The main character feels one strong feeling: pride. He takes his little brother, Doodle, on many adventures. But Doodle is very sick and cannot do the things the main character wants him to do. The main character is very unhappy about this. He wishes he had a brother he could teach and play with. He wanted a brother to share his life with. But Doodle's sickness makes this impossible.

The main character is even angry with Doodle sometimes. He even thought about hurting him. But when Doodle smiles, the main character feels happy. This shows that he truly loves his brother. He wants to help Doodle and make him happy.

The brain is a very complicated part of our body. It helps us think and learn. As time has passed, people have used different ideas to explain how the brain works. First, people thought of the brain like a piece of paper. Then they thought of it like a book. Now, many people think of it like a computer. However, these ideas are not perfect and can lead to mistakes.

Information comes into the brain from our senses. Our senses are our eyes, ears, nose, tongue, and skin. They turn things like touch, heat, sound, and light into signals. The brain changes these signals many times. This helps us understand what we see and hear.

There are two ways the brain changes these signals. One way is from small pieces of information to bigger pieces. The other way is from using what we know to help us understand things faster. For example, if you see a picture of a box, the brain first puts together small pieces of information like color and shape. Then, it uses what we know to decide that it is a box.

The brain also decides which signals are important and which ones we should pay attention to. For example, when you look at your shoes, your brain doesn't notice every single blade of grass. But if someone says your name, you might hear it even in a noisy room.

The brain has different ways to store information. There are three types: sensory, working, and long-term memory. First, the brain must put the information into a form it can understand. There are different ways to do this, like looking at what a word looks like, hearing how it sounds, or knowing what it means.

Once the information is stored, the brain must keep it. Some studies with animals show that working memory, which lasts about 20 seconds, is like a signal in a special group of brain cells. Long-term memory is thought to be kept in the shape of certain proteins.

There are many ways to think about how the brain stores and uses information. Some ideas come from how people remember things, others come from computer science, and others come from studying the brain. One idea is that the brain uses nodes, like links in a chain, to connect related ideas. For example, "chair" might be connected to "table," which is connected to "wooden," and so on.

Aldous Huxley wrote a book called Brave New World. It is a story about a bad future where people are controlled by a person called the World Controller. The people in this story do not value the individual. They value the community above all else. They are taught to be happy from a young age. But they are not really free. They are like pawns in a game.

Huxley was afraid of a future where people are controlled by technology and money. He showed this in his story. The people in the story are not allowed to think for themselves. They do what they are told. They are not allowed to love or feel strong emotions. They just want to be happy and not be unhappy.

Huxley used ideas from Marxism in his story. In Marxism, people who are poor and work hard are kept down by people who are rich and powerful. In Brave New World, the poor people are kept down by the World Controller and the rich people who are born with special bodies and brains. They call these people Alphas and Betas. They are in charge and the others have to do what they are told.

The people in the story do not know that they are being controlled. They just want to be happy and have fun. They do not know about the people who are in charge and how they are being controlled. Huxley showed this in his story. He made it seem like the people in the story are happy, but really they are not free.

The people in the story do not have relationships with each other. They just interact with each other in a shallow way. They do not love each other or feel deep emotions. They are just like machines. Huxley was showing how people can become like machines if they are controlled by technology and money.

Huxley was warning people about the dangers of a future where people are controlled by technology and money. He showed how people can become like machines and lose their free will. He showed how people can be kept down by those in power and not know it.

I have been a student here at University Park for two and a half years. Traveling on campus can be hard for many students, including me. My first year, I lived in an East Halls dorm room. It was far from the center of campus. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in Willard building, near the center, could take 25 minutes on foot. The weather in State College is often bad.

I talked to an old student. He said that not long ago, East Halls was far from the rest of campus. Now, there are many new buildings and apartments. As the campus grows, getting from one place to another gets harder. The best way to solve mobility problems on campus is with a bike. But bikes alone are not enough. Students must ride them, and the campus must be made for bicyclists.

I talked to a friend who rode a bike again after a few years. He said, “Bikes are great. They are the best way to get around.” Besides being good for your body, biking is the most efficient way to travel. I live off campus, not near the center of campus. Last year, I bought a bike. It was a smart decision. I have class in Thomas building, a 25-minute walk from my home. If I ride my bike fast, it only takes 5 minutes. However, Pollock Road is not easy to ride on. I like biking because I am too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would take too much time. Every week, it would be over two and a half hours. I don’t have time for that.

original_texts:
In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD. 

	CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

	In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

Downwards I stared, mind blankly comprehending the view in front of me.  Unemotionally, silently, with a practiced awareness that studied but refused to relate the object of study to any abstract understanding my mind analyzed the picture before my eyes.  Thoughts slipped into my mind and slipped out again almost faster than they appeared.  So smoothly and so cleanly my consciousness worked that it seemed I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and liquid experience of what I was looking at. 
Once, on advice from an artist I worked with, I purchased an art instruction book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain.   I had wanted to learn how to draw ever since I was six years old and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to processes the brain uses to interpret lines.  One technique the book teaches is to place a square frame around any picture the artist wishes to study.  Thus transforming an overwhelmingly detailed picture, for instance a bowl of fruit sitting on a table located in a kitchen that is connected to a dining room, into an easily grasped picture, that bowl of fruit sitting on a simple plane.   
At the time, staring down at the bowl in front of me I could not mentally project that artist’s frame.  I was so overwhelmed, so awed that I could only stand and gaze in wonderment.  Picasso went through his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of casting my perspective as worthy of the title Artistic then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, Work in Brown.  
Fingertips alighted on my chosen implement of artistry, muscles tightened and relaxed as my hand passed through space, my mind’s will given shape and form in what could have been the most creative moment of my life.  Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean.  Flakes of matter broke away from the whole and were carried away to nothingness.  Muscles tightening, jerking and spasming a little more quickly and anxious the second time, my hand smacked the handle of the toilet again.  The offensive brown package refused to move, stuck like a slug on the bottom of the toilet.  
Mop gripped loosely in hand, feet set a foot apart, green tie knotted uncomfortably around my throat, I frowned slightly as I stared at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter someone had left as a message for the suckers who cleaned the bathrooms at Rite Aid.  A few flushes more, a few more tranquil introspective moments to myself, then my hand moved towards the wall to my right, gripped the sheet at the end of the toilet paper, and began mummifying itself until it resembled an oven mitt.   Standing up straight, then bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the bowl, like a mother going into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey….

Teenagers are dying behind the wheel.  Several factors come together to create this deadly vector of statistics for the youngest American drivers.  The National Institutes of Health explain that one facet of the problem is that the teen brain is literally not ready for the hazards of driving. Simple inexperience also lies at the heart of the problem. This inexperience not only causes more fatal accidents, but also a higher rate of vehicle rollover, speeding, and driving off the road.  
Teens also fare far worse when they travel with their peers—which anyone with an iota of sense knows they do on a regular basis.  The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study that showed the following correlation: between the age of the passenger and the number of traffic accidents occurring.
	California and other states have attempted to increase the safety of teen drivers by requiring temporary provisional licenses that limit the hours that teens may drive and prohibit other minors as passengers.
	But provisional driver’s licenses are, in my opinion, stopgap measures.  The real issue is that—as a group—the youngest drivers are, by all statistical markers, simply not able to adequately handle the risks and responsibilities.  Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 is too young for a regular driver’s license.  USA Today reports that Zuckerman has performed research suggesting a common desire among those under the age of 19-20 to take risks for the sheer thrill of the sensation.  It makes sense then, to delay driving at least until the tendency to thrill-seek has begun to level out.  If we continue to issue driver’s licenses to young teens, we will not only continue to see deadly accidents happening, but the death toll is likely to reach staggering proportions in the next few years.  By 2010, the Baby-Boomer’s babies will be eligible to drive and millions of new teen drivers will ready to hit the road.  
Legislation dealing with this issue would be reasonably straightforward.  Schools could continue to provide driver’s education classes to begin the learning process for future drivers, but no one under the age of 18 could operate a motor vehicle.  A provisional permit could still be issued prior to granting a full driver’s license, and a certain number of practical driver’s training hours would still be required as well.  The specific number of hours required could be based on the number of hours already required by the majority of states (in California, for example, that number is currently 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult.)  Because the deadly statistics for teen drivers come from a cross-section of all states, uniform, national legislation on this issue would be a reasonable—and I believe effective—means of protecting teens across the nation. 
The legislation I suggest is by no means a novel idea.

In looking through the Library of Congress’s library of early Edison films, I decided to view all of the trick films, of which there were fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films generally take advantage of creative editing to produce illusions. My film study generally focused on describing the poetics for the majority of trick films and examining the evolutionary outlier characteristics present in a few of the later films. Largely, the trick film at the turn of the century is set-bound, composed within a frontal proscenium, features no camera movement, uses long and medium shots, and adheres to the strict one shot = one film methodology. However, there are some films at the beginning of the twentieth century that dare to break these guidelines by introducing aspects such as multiple shots.
One of the most noticeable aspects that the trick films share in common is their filming in an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films, and drew its root from the theatre and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One of the limitations inherent in the use of the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side, and do not walk towards or away from the camera. Take, for example, the action in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even as they go out of the frame, the camera does not follow them.
The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-up shots are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This borrows from the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at any given time, framed by the borders of the stage. As in most early films, the actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.
Generally, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative usage of the trick films; most of them focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. Note, however, that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer’s eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single “shot” may actually be several joined together to produce the illusion of apparition or disappearing. Look carefully at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A more thorough inspection reveals the moment where the physical shot with Mary’s severed “head” begins, even though the whole film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

‎	‏John Taylor of Caroline was an early and ardent proponent of Republicanism.  Though he was primarily an agriculturalist,‭ ‬that very profession along with his brief career in politics created a man known for his dedication and outspokenness in matters of personal freedom and government.  His dedication to an agrarian system was the basis for almost all of his opinions concerning the government.  It was his attempt to preserve and encourage what he considered the most superior of all careers that colored his arguments on sovereignty,‭ ‬Constitutionality,‭ ‬and even the judicial system.
‎	‏John Taylor believed that the United States had a great opportunity to create an ideal system,‭ ‬because there was no native tradition to hinder the creators of the government,‭ ‬which allowed for the establishment of a system of self-government.  He believed strongly in the natural rights of man,‭ ‬and in the fact that they are all interdependent—meaning that if one is denied,‭ ‬then they all will fail,‭ ‬and the value of those remaining is lessened.
